record.text: Teletext Around the World, Still https://hackaday.com/2025/08/15/teletext-around-the-world-still/ #Retrocomputing #teletext #videotex

external.description:
When you mention Teletext or Videotex, you probably think of the 1970s British system, the well-known system in France, or the short-lived US attempt to launch the service. Before the Internet, there were all kinds of crazy ways to deliver customized information into people’s homes. Old-fashioned? Turns out Teletext is alive and well in many parts of the world, and [text-mode] has the story of both the past and the present with a global perspective.

The whole thing grew out of the desire to send closed caption text. In 1971, Philips developed a way to do that by using the vertical blanking interval that isn’t visible on a TV. Of course, there needed to be a standard, and since standards are such a good thing, the UK developed three different ones.

The TVs of the time weren’t exactly the high-resolution devices we think of these days, so the 1976 level one allowed for regular (but Latin) characters and an alternate set of blocky graphics you could show on an expansive 40×24 palette in glorious color as long as you think seven colors is glorious. Level 1.5 added characters the rest of the world might want, and this so-called “World System Teletext” is still the basis of many systems today. It was better, but still couldn’t handle the 134 characters in Vietnamese.

Meanwhile, the French also wanted in on the action and developed Antiope, which had more capabilities. The United States would, at least partially, adopt this standard as well. In fact, the US fragmented between both systems along with a third system out of Canada until they converged on AT&T’s PLP system, renamed as North American Presentation Layer Syntax or NAPLPS. The post makes the case that NAPLPS was built on both the Canadian and French systems.

That was in 1986, and the Internet was getting ready to turn all of these developments, like $200 million Canadian system, into a roaring dumpster fire. The French even abandoned their homegrown system in favor of the World System Teletext. The post says as of 2024, at least 15 countries still maintain teletext.

So that was the West. What about behind the Iron Curtain, the Middle East, and in Asia? Well, that’s the last part of the post, and you should definitely check it out.

Japan’s version of teletex, still in use as of the mid-1990s, was one of the most advanced.

If you are interested in the underlying technology, teletext data lives in the vertical blanking interval between frames on an analog TV system. Data had page numbers. If you requested a page, the system would either retrieve it from a buffer or wait for it to appear in the video signal. Some systems send a page at a time, while others send bits of a page on each field. In theory, the three-digit page number can range from 100 to 0x8FF, although in practice, too many pages slow down the system, and normal users can’t key in hex numbers.

For PAL, for example, the data resides in even lines between 6 and 22, or in lines 318 to 335 for odd lines. Systems can elect to use fewer lines. A black signal is a zero, while a 66% white signal is a one, and the data is in NRZ line coding. There is a framing code to identify where the data starts. Other systems have slight variations, but the overall bit rate is around 5 to 6 Mbit/s. Character speeds are slightly slower due to error correction and other overhead.

Honestly, we thought this was all ancient history. You have to wonder which country will be the last one standing as the number of Teletext systems continues to dwindle. Of course, we still have closed captions, but with digital television, it really isn’t the same thing. Can Teletext run Doom? Apparently, yes, if you stretch your definition of success a bit.
external.title: Teletext Around The World, Still

Around it, thick wooden shelves are stacked with tightly rolled scrolls, their cylindrical forms echoing the curves of the fox’s own wrappings. These scrolls seem to hum with silent history, each one a vessel of forgotten wisdom, resting in patient slumber.

Six candles encircle the fox in a loose ritual arrangement, their flames swaying softly as if breathing in sync with the figure’s unspoken thoughts. The golden light of their glow carves out a halo of warmth amid the surrounding dusk, painting the scene in tones of aged paper, honey, and burnished bronze. The shadows between shelves deepen into mystery, suggesting corridors of memory stretching beyond sight.

The air is thick with the scent of wax and parchment, carrying a weight of patience, of watchfulness. It is a place where stories are not just read but lived, where the figure seems to exist as both keeper and embodiment of the archive’s soul.

This is less a mere image than a moment suspended—quiet, reverent, and eternal.

A white-furred rabbit, anthropomorphic yet brimming with human emotion, sits at a desk, framed by the muted geometry of filing cabinets and bookshelves. Her eyes, deep pools of concentrated ire, lock forward with an intensity that could slice through steel. Her brow is furrowed, each line etched with a conviction that brooks no nonsense.

Clutched in her left paw is the receiver of a most peculiar telephone—shaped like a bright orange fish, with a comically wide, startled eye. The absurdity of its design only magnifies the gravity of her mood, creating a delicate tension between whimsy and wrath. The coiled black cord dangles like a tense spring, its curves leading the eye toward her clenched right fist, a silent punctuation of her frustration.

Her shirt is a muted coral-pink, a warm counterpoint to the cool shadows in the background, its simple lines framing her upright, confrontational posture. The lighting is soft but decisive, casting subtle shadows that add weight to her expression without drowning her in gloom. Through the glass panel behind her, the blurred interior of another room hints at an unseen world, yet all focus remains pinned to the raw, animated immediacy of her glare.

It’s a moment caught mid-sentence, where the air is thick with unsaid words, the absurd fish-shaped receiver pressed to her ear as though it might bite back. The image blends humor and sincerity so perfectly that it feels both like a still from a whimsical animated drama and a timeless portrait of determination.

Its wool glows in soft, celestial blues, each curl of fleece dotted with radiant stardust that twinkles like whispers of forgotten wishes. A single, larger star rests upon its flank—a beacon of purity and quiet wonder—shining brighter than the rest, as though it carries a secret known only to the night.

The lamb’s eyes are wide and warm, filled with an innocent curiosity, gazing ahead at a small, hovering UFO—an unexpected companion in this infinite playground of space. Around them, countless pinprick stars glimmer in gradients of icy silver and soft sapphire, scattered like precious gems across an endless ocean of midnight. The darkness is not empty but alive—full of mystery, serenity, and the gentle hum of eternity.

There is a dreamlike stillness here, the kind found only in the spaces between moments. The composition feels light and whimsical, yet laced with the magic of something boundless, as though the lamb is not just leaping through the sky, but through the very fabric of imagination itself.

The scene unfolds like a tender stop-motion dream, where every curve and detail seems lovingly sculpted by gentle hands. Two anthropomorphic rabbits sit side by side on a rustic wooden porch, bathed in the molten gold of a setting sun. Their oversized, soulful green eyes gleam with quiet contentment, reflecting the horizon’s warm glow. The male rabbit, bare-chested with tousled black hair that cascades in clay-like strands, leans slightly toward his companion, their fingers entwined in a silent exchange of affection. Beside him, the female rabbit mirrors his posture, her own hair a waterfall of sculpted midnight curls, crowned by a delicate pink flower that whispers of spring.

In their hands, they cradle steaming mugs, tendrils of vapor spiraling into the cool evening air like whispered secrets. The porch planks beneath them glow in the low light, each grain of wood catching the amber kiss of dusk. Behind them, a green door with a copper knob hints at a cozy home, while a lantern hangs unlit, unnecessary in the golden tide of day’s end.

Beyond the porch rail, rolling hills melt into the distance, their contours softened by the sun’s retreat, as if the world itself is exhaling. The atmosphere hums with serenity—an unhurried heartbeat of love, companionship, and the kind of peace found only in shared silences. The wall weeps limestone tears.

Her coat – a bell.
Wind? No wind.
The sun strikes her cheek – hot!

And ever since, and ever since,
The brick-shadows crawl over the asphalt's face,
Seeking a way out.
But there is no way out.
Only the wall.
Only the plaster's weeping.
Only the game.
